05461nam a22008055i 9780812299588DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122995887 a10.9783/97808122995882doi  a(DE-B1597)573135  a(OCoLC)1244629596  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aHIS0410002bisacsh04a306.362097292231 aStone, Erin Woodruff, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCaptives of Conquest :bSlavery in the Early Modern Spanish Caribbean /cErin Woodruff Stone. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b6 b/w  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Early Modern Americas00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction. From a “Structure of Conjuncture” to a “Shatter Zone” -- tChapter 1. Migration, Exchange, and Conquest: Slavery in the Pre- Contact Atlantic -- tChapter 2. Two Worlds Collide: The Rise of the Indian Slave Trade -- tChapter 3. The Ties That Bind: Religious Orders and Indian Caciques on Española, 1500–1534 -- tChapter 4. The Search for Slaves Inspires New World Exploration -- tChapter 5. Granjerías de Indios: The Business of Indigenous Slavery -- tChapter 6. Crossroads of Slavery: The African Slave Trade Meets the Indian Slave Trade -- tConclusion. The Slow Decline of the Indian Slave Trade -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCaptives of Conquest is one of the first books to examine the earliest indigenous slave trade in the Spanish Caribbean. Erin Woodruff Stone shows that the indigenous population of the region did not simply collapse from disease or warfare. Rather, upwards of 250,000 people were removed through slavery, a lucrative business sustained over centuries that formed the foundation of economic, legal, and religious policies in the Spanish colonies. The enslavement of and trade in indigenous peoples was central to the processes of conquest, as the search for new sources of Indian slaves propelled much of the early Spanish exploration into Central and South America.Once captured, some indigenous slaves were shipped to various islands, or as far away as Spain, to be sold for immediate profit. Others became military auxiliaries, guides, miners, pearl divers, servants, or, in the case of women, unwilling sexual partners. In all these roles indigenous slaves helped mold the greater Spanish Caribbean.Even as the number of African slaves grew in the Americas, enslaved Indians did not disappear. On the contrary, African and Indian slaves worked side by side, the methods and practices of both types of slavery influencing one another throughout the centuries. Together the two forms of slavery helped create the greater Spanish Caribbean, a space and economy founded upon the bondage and coerced labor of both indigenous and African peoples.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aSlave tradezWest IndiesxHistory. 0aSlaveryzWest IndiesxHistory. 0aSlaveszWest IndiesxSocial conditions. 4aHistory-United States. 7aHISTORY / Caribbean & West Indies / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.  aCaribbean Studies.  aLatin American Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Complete eBoo